<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> was `` vastly improved'' and giving the thumbs-up sign to her hospital nurse Sunday following a near-drowning in her swimming pool. `` She's in good spirits now because she knows she's going to get well,'' said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deaton </PERSON>, a lung specialist treating Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>. `` She's emotional about that and a little bit teary-eyed some of the time, knowing what she's been through and how close she came to a real catastrophic event. But she still also has her jovial personality. She was joking a little bit this morning,'' <PERSON> Deaton </PERSON> said. `` She is vastly improved.'' Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>'s condition was upgraded from critical to serious but stable, and she continued to improve Sunday night. `` She started her liquid diet tonight. She is breathing on her own. She is receiving supplemental oxygen, though,'' hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Kari </PERSON> <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, 52, who gained national attention during the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> impeachment hearings, was flown by emergency helicopter to <LOCATION> Brackenridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> on Saturday after she was found floating face-down in her pool. <PERSON> Deaton </PERSON> said she came within `` four to five minutes, 10 minutes at most'' of suffering severe brain damage and possibly death. Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> apparently lost consciousness while in the pool. <PERSON> Deaton </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Little </PERSON>, a neurologist, said it is n't known what caused her to lose consciousness, but that the lack of oxygen then caused cardiac arrest. Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> had been in critical condition in the hospital's intensive care unit, but <PERSON> Deaton </PERSON> said Sunday afternoon that `` she's upgraded She's certainly stable, in a much less serious condition.'' Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> was breathing without the aid of a mechanical ventilator, responding to questions and trying to make sure a Monday dental appointment was canceled. `` She obviously has pretty good mental recall if that's her biggest concern,'' <PERSON> Deaton </PERSON> said. `` Right now, I think things look very good that she'll get totally back to normal,'' <PERSON> Little </PERSON> said. `` She's very close to normal right now. I think she will continue to improve. As best as I can tell right now, she probably will regain full mental functions.'' The doctors said Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, who has used a wheelchair for several years, suffers from multiple sclerosis but her condition should n't have had an effect on the incident. `` She has muscle weakness and it would be difficult for her to rescue herself from the swimming pool if she had any warning of any event. ... I doubt, though, based on the suddenness of the event, that she had any warning,'' <PERSON> Deaton </PERSON> said. Little said possible causes for her losing consciousness were a sudden heartbeat irregularity or a seizure. But hospital tests showed `` her cardiac status has been very stable. She's had no evidence of seizure activity,'' he said. Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> delivered a nominating speech for vice presidential candidate Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> at the Democratic National Convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> telephoned a message to Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> on Sunday, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON>. Visitors to the hospital have included <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Treasurer <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>, who delivered the keynote address at the convention; <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostow </PERSON>, a former aide to President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> women's basketball Coach <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Conradt </PERSON>; plus Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>'s two sisters and live-in companion, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON>, who found Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> in the pool. Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> is a fan of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lady </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Longhorns </ORGANIZATION>, and nurse <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said the basketball team's former star, <PERSON> Fran </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, visited before leaving for the Olympic trials. `` When I remember seeing Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> on TV, I frequently remember the thumbs-up sign that things are OK. She's probably given me that about 20 times today,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> in 1966 became the first black state senator in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> history. In 1972, she was the first Southern black elected to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> since Reconstruction, serving until 1978, when she left politics after three terms in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to teach at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION>.
