<DATELINE>BOLZANO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three bombs exploded Sunday in the northern province of <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Adige </LOCATION>, injuring one person and damaging about 30 cars, police said. Authorities blamed the blasts on German-speaking extremists seeking autonomy for the province. Thirteen bombs attributed to the extremists have gone off since March, but none have caused deaths or serious injuries. Police said one bomb exploded in a garbage bin in the city of <LOCATION> Bolzano </LOCATION> at about 4:30 a.m., injuring a 65-year-old man who was cut by flying glass. Windows and cars were also damaged, they said. At about the same time, two bombs exploded at a hydroelectric plant in <LOCATION> Ponte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gardena </LOCATION>, about 10 miles north of <LOCATION> Bolzano </LOCATION>. One of the plant's three power transformers was heavily damaged by one explosion and a resulting fire, police said. State-owned RAI television said about $ 750,000 in damage was done to the plant owned by <PERSON> Selm </PERSON>, a subsidiary of the chemical company <ORGANIZATION> Montedison </ORGANIZATION>. A second bomb exploded in a field about 100 yards from the houses of eight Italian-speaking plant workers, but caused no serious damage. On the plant's gates, investigators found an envelope on which was scrawled in German `` <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tyrol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Combat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>,'' a name left at other bomb sites. German inhabitants refer to the province as <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tyrol </LOCATION>. The Alto Adige province was stripped from <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> after World War I. The 300,000 ethnic German-speakers are a majority and have demanded priority in government jobs and more control over local broadcasting. Extremists want an independent Tyrolian state. After a terrorism campaign in the 1960s, the Italian government made the province officially bilingual.
