<FIRST>r w AM-InflationFears Bjt   07-31 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inflation Fears, Bjt,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Economists Believe High Inflation Poised for Return</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New government statistics have revived the debate over whether the evil inflation monster, which terrorized <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> during the 1970s, is starting to awaken after having slept for most of this decade. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, mindful of how voters' perceptions will affect the presidential race, insists there are no signs that inflation is becoming a problem. But many private economists disagree. These economists contend that the 68-month economic expansion, now the second longest of the post-World War II period, has used up all of the economy's slack capacity. Tight labor markets and high factory operating rates are beginning to be translated into accelerating wage demands and higher prices, they believe. Proponents of this theory received more ammunition last week with two new government reports, one on wage increases and the other on overall economic growth and inflation. The wage report showed that compensation for American workers, wages and fringe benefits such as health insurance and pensions, was rising this year at the highest rate since the summer of 1985. Wages and benefits, which represent about two-thirds of all business costs, climbed by 4.5 percent in the 12-month period ending in June, compared with an increase of just 3 percent in the prior 12 months. In a second report, the government said an inflation index tied to the gross national product shot up at an annual rate of 4.7 percent from April through June, the fastest pace in almost six years. The big jump in prices was blamed on higher consumer costs for food, clothing and energy. To the administration, these reports were not cause for concern. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, the president's chief economic adviser, blamed the inflation spurt on temporary factors, including the drought and higher import costs because of the weaker dollar. He insisted that there was no evidence that the economy was being overtaken by a new wage-price spiral. `` We remain convinced that inflation will continue under restraint,'' he told reporters during a briefing. Some private economists agree, contending that inflationary pressures from the drought and tight labor markets are being offset by weakness in oil prices and a rebound in the dollar, which reduces the costs of imports. They note that the consumer price index, after registering big jumps in the early spring, calmed down in May and June only 0.3 percent. During the first six months of the year, consumer prices rose 4.4 percent, identical to the inflation rate for all of 1987. `` I do n't think we are seeing signs of higher inflation ahead,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, head of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consulting firm. `` The rise in energy and clothing prices in the spring has since been reversed.'' But this view is disputed by other private analysts, who argue that inflation has once again become a threat for the first time since the early 1980s, when the fight to reduce double-digit inflation rates led to the steep 1981-82 recession. `` The pickup in inflation is worrisome and is likely to continue through the end of the year, raising the possibility of a slowdown in growth in 1989,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasinowski </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>. Other analysts raise the possibility of an outright recession beginning next year. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> since March has been taking a series of steps to push interest rates higher in an effort to ease inflationary pressures by dampening demand. While this is the classic recipe for starting a recession, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> has maintained that a downturn can be avoided if the central bank acts quickly at the first sign of inflation, when the amount of credit restraint needed is still small. But <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> may have already waited too long. `` The pattern is that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> always waits too long to act, then it clamps down too hard and causes a recession,'' he said. <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has been hesitant about moving too quickly because this is a presidential election year and big interest-rate boosts would not be viewed favorably by the administration in its efforts to keep the White House in Republican hands. As a result, <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> predicted that consumer prices would rise at around 5.5 percent annual rate next year, which would be the fastest inflation clip since an 8.9 percent rise in 1981. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said one of the problems is that demand pressures are outstripping the country's ability to produce the goods and services `` We are starting to see a situation where we have too many dollars chasing too few goods,'' he said. `` Once the economy runs out of slack, we often get a credit crunch, which ultimately leads to a recession.''
