ild care. It costs the Department of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> about $ 4 billion a year in lost revenue. According to <PERSON> Blank </PERSON>, other government child-care programs include a $ 2.7 billion social services block grant to states, of which less than 20 percent is used for day care, and a $ 600 million food program that helps day-care homes and centers provide nutritious meals. Welfare parents in job training programs or jobs that do n't pay enough for them to leave the rolls are also entitled to some help with child-care expenses. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> bill, endorsed in general terms by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, would depart from current policy by giving tax breaks to families with a spouse at home _ families not eligible for the existing dependent care tax credit. At least four Republican-sponsored bills pending in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> take the same approach. Conservatives support it as a way to eliminate what they see as tax discrimination against mothers who decide to stay home with their children. But Citizens for <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, a labor-backed tax study group, said the bills are unfair and unlikely to help those most in need, since low-income families can least afford to have one parent stay at home. Backers of the Democratic initiative say a universal tax break for families with preschool children is no substitute for their bill. They argue that a $ 1,000 tax credit would pay for only a third of the cost of one child's annual day care, and after the fact. They say a simple tax credit does not address the uneven quality of day care. Conservatives criticize the Democrats' bill on two major points _ its cost and the federal day-care standards it sets. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan and a recent House GOP initiative with a $ 1.3 billion price tag may blunt the controversy over spending That leaves federal standards for child-care as the