<HEAD>Church Accuses Government of Persecution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEDRO SERVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Paraguayan Roman Catholic church, in a statement read Sunday at churches throughout the country, said it is being persecuted by the government of President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>. It called on the government to `` respect the fundamental rights of human dignity.'' On Saturday, the church announced the suspension of a <ORGANIZATION> Te </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mass </ORGANIZATION>, a service of thanksgiving, that had been scheduled for Aug. 15. Both actions were taken in response to the expulsion last Monday of a Spanish-born Jesuit priest, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, who was accused of advocating rebellion. The statement read at the Masses Sunday said in part: `` We recently have observed repressive acts that affect and seriously violate the dignity of the people, such as arbitrary arrests, limitations on freedom of expression and, once again, the expulsion of a priest from the country.'' The message had the title, `` A situation of persecution of the church due to arbitrary expulsion of Father <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> de la Vega.'' It was drawn up by the <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the country's about 800 priests. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, a 65-year-old theology professor, was arrested and deported to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> on July 25. The government accused him of publicly advocating the violent overthrow of the government in comments he made at a conference on Liberation Theology. Church officials denied the claim and said de la <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> had been explaining Liberation Theology, a movement that seeks political change as a way to achieve social reform. The archbishop of <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ismael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rolon </PERSON>, sent a note to the government Saturday announcing cancellation of the Te Deum Mass held annually to mark the anniversary of the Aug. 15, 1537, founding of the city of <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>. This year the date coincides with the inauguration of Gen. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> for an eighth consecutive term as president. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, 75, has ruled the country since he seized power in a 1954 coup supported by the armed forces and the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He was re-elected to a new term, with 88.6 percent of the vote, in elections in February. Opposition parties called the balloting fraudulent. Te Deum Masses were canceled on two previous occasions in the last 20 years _ in November 1969 and May 1972. Both followed the government's expulsion of priests. A total of 21 foreign-born priests and religious workers, most of them natives of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, have been expelled since <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> took power. <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> leaders have been frequent critics of <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s authoritarian rule
