<HEAD>Poe House Designated National Literary Landmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the six <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> homes of author and poet <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Poe </PERSON> was designated a National Literary Landmark on Sunday because of its importance in the writer's career. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, acting supervisory ranger at the <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Poe </PERSON> National Historic Site, said the house is the only one remaining of <PERSON> Poe </PERSON>'s houses in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, where he lived from 1838 to 1844. <PERSON> Poe </PERSON>'s time in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> is considered among his most productive, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` Most of his famous works were published here,'' he said. They included `` The Tell-Tale Heart,'' `` The Murders in the Rue Morgue,'' `` The Gold Bug,'' `` The Pit and the Pendulum,'' and `` The Black Cat,'' said <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>. However, it is not known whether <PERSON> Poe </PERSON> actually composed those works while living in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> because his manuscripts were n't dated. The historical site, which became part of Independence National Historical Park in 1981, includes the house he rented and a neighbor's house. The Literary Landmarks Association is a <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, Ohio-based group that designates sites important to the lives of famous authors. <PERSON> Poe </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> in 1809 and died in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> in 1849.
